				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">What Responsibility Do We Have to Take In Refugees From Global Humanitarian Crises?</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Michael Gonchar			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-11-24T10:00:39+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 24, 2015 5:00 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 24, 2015 5:00 am</span>		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/23/us/24refugees-web7-LN/24refugees-web7-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/23/us/24refugees-web7-LN/24refugees-web7-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/23/us/24refugees-web7-LN/24refugees-web7-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000004054174" width="592" height="395" alt="Nayef Buteh, 45, right, his wife, Feryal Jabur, 41, and their 8-year-old son, Arab, arrived in Detroit last week. The family left Syria in 2013 for a refugee camp in Jordan. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/24/us/syrian-refugees-cling-to-a-longtime-haven-in-michigan.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Nayef Buteh, 45, right, his wife, Feryal Jabur, 41, and their 8-year-old son, Arab, arrived in Detroit last week. The family left Syria in 2013 for a refugee camp in Jordan. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/24/us/syrian-refugees-cling-to-a-longtime-haven-in-michigan.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Salwan Georges for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/11/24/what-responsibility-do-we-have-to-take-in-refugees-from-global-humanitarian-crises/" data-title="What Responsibility Do We Have to Take In Refugees From Global Humanitarian Crises?" data-description="How do we find an appropriate balance between our moral responsibility and any security concerns we might have?">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_student-opinion151.png" alt="Student Opinion - The Learning Network" /></a><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/"><img class="w35 right" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_student-opinion35.png" alt="Student Opinion - The Learning Network" /></a></p>
<p class="summary">Questions about issues in the news for students 13 and older.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/">See all Student Opinion Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the wake of the terrorist attacks in Paris, many politicians &#8212; particularly <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/11/17/us/politics/presidential-candidates-on-syrian-refugees.html">Republicans</a> &#8212; have tried to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/17/us/politics/gop-governors-vow-to-close-doors-to-syrian-refugees.html">stop</a> or <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/20/us/politics/house-refugees-syria-iraq.html">slow</a> the admission of Syrian refugees to the United States.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Does the United States have a moral responsibility to admit refugees from the world&#8217;s biggest global humanitarian crises, like the Syrian civil war? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-164078"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In &#8220;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/24/us/syrian-refugees-cling-to-a-longtime-haven-in-michigan.html">Syrian Refugees Cling to a Longtime Haven in Michigan</a>,&#8221;  Julie Bosman writes about Syrian refugees already living in the United States:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. â In late 2011, as killings, kidnappings and sectarian strife crept across its battle-scarred city of Homs, Syria, the family of four made a sorrowful decision: to flee.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Radwan Mughrbel; his wife, Sanaa Hammadeh; and their two young sons packed their bags with only a single change of clothes per person. They took a bus to Damascus and hired a taxi to spirit them across the border into Jordan. For years, they patched together a meager life, barely making enough money to eat and desperately seeking refugee status.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When the United Nations refugee agency asked where they wanted to go, the answer was obvious.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAmerica,â said Mr. Mughrbel, a short, wiry Muslim man of 52, his face lighting up in a smile as he sat in his bare-walled living room in this Detroit suburb last week. âThey brought us here, and I feel safe, like nothing bad can happen to us. Now we have a beautiful life.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet that beautiful life has been shaken. Since the terrorist attacks in Paris, a tide of anti-refugee, anti-Muslim sentiment has swept, angrily and inexorably, across the United States. Now Mr. Mughrbel and Ms. Hammadeh say Michigan is not as welcoming a place as it was before.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Gov. Rick Snyder, who in September publicly rhapsodized about the boon that refugees were to Michiganâs economy, was among the first of more than two dozen Republican governors to vow last week that they would try to keep displaced Syrians out of their states to preserve the safety of Americans from would-be terrorists.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Presidential candidates and elected officials around the country have suggested closing mosques, collecting Syrian refugees already in the country or creating a registry for Muslims.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sentiments like those are especially jarring in Michigan, which has one of the largest and most vibrant Arab-American populations in the country and a vocal group of advocates for bringing more Syrian refugees to the United States. In the Detroit suburbs, refugees have traded a harrowing war in the Middle East for cold winters, strip malls and neatly arranged subdivisions, with houses as uniform as Monopoly pieces.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The United States has accepted more than 1,800 Syrian refugees since October 2014. Michigan has welcomed close to 200 â more than any other state except California and Texas. The Obama administration has said it wants to bring in at least 10,000 in the next year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Those plans have been threatened by the sudden and contentious debate over whether these refugees, many of them young children, are security threats. On Thursday, the Republican-led House voted overwhelmingly to impose new screening procedures on refugees from Syria. After Gov. Mike Pence of Indiana, a Republican, said he did not want any more Syrian refugees in his state, one Syrian family destined for Indianapolis was rerouted to Connecticut.
</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students:</strong> Read the entire article, then tell us &#8230;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â What responsibility do we have to take in refugees from global humanitarian crises in Syria, Iraq and elsewhere? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â How do we find an appropriate balance between our moral responsibility and any security concerns we might have?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â Nicholas Kristof writes:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Letâs be real: Refugee admission is the most deeply vetted pathway into the United States. Even for Iraqis who worked as translators for our military, risking their lives to keep Americans alive and enjoying strong support of American officers, vetting can take a couple of years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thatâs why the 9/11 attackers didnât enter the U.S. as refugees, but as students and tourists. If a terrorist group wants to attack America, it wonât wait two years to try to infiltrate as refugees. Itâll send people in as students or tourists, use fake or stolen U.S. or European passports, or just pay a human smuggler to take their terrorists across the border from Mexico or Canada.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do you think making the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/11/20/us/why-it-takes-two-years-for-syrian-refugees-to-apply-to-enter-the-united-states.html">vetting process</a> more difficult for Syrian refugees is smart policy, or is it just playing into irrational fears &#8212; especially since, as far as we know, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/11/15/world/europe/manhunt-for-paris-attackers.html">none of the Paris attackers</a> was Syrian? If we want to prevent foreign terrorists from entering the United States, are there other actions we should take instead? Why?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â Two events from American history have recently been compared on social media and in the news to the debate about Syrian refugees: the internment of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/21/us/roanoke-mayor-apologizes-for-japanese-internment-remarks.html">Japanese-Americans</a> after Pearl Harbor and the United States&#8217; refusal to take in <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/11/20/us/comparing-jewish-refugees-of-the-1930s-with-syrians-today.html">Jewish refugees</a> fleeing Nazi Germany. In what ways is the focus on Syrian refugees after the Paris attacks similar or different to these historical examples?   </p>
<hr />
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/14/border-challenges-responding-to-the-global-migration-crisis/">Related Lesson Plan | Border Challenges: Responding to the Global Migration Crisis</a></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students 13 and older</strong> are invited to comment below. All comments are moderated by the Learning Network staff, but please keep in mind that once your comment is accepted, it will be made public.</p>
<hr />
	</div>
